Welcome to Falcon Stadium:

We welcome you, your team, cheerleaders, band, and spectators to our field. Prior to arrival, we wish to give a few guidelines we ask our visitors to follow.

As per UIL Guidelines, we are observing 50% capacity for all home games.

Visiting fans will enter and exit through the East gate near the baseball field.
We ask fans to wear a face covering at all times and maintain social distancing.
Children should remain with their parents at all times.
We have a full concession stand available as well as other concession items offered by various student organizations.

Click the link for tickets
https://gofan.co/app/events/100925

Or
Scan the QR Code with another device (camera) to capture the link and purchase tickets.

post_text:
Canadian Community,
In keeping with Canadian ISD’s practices to respond to COVID-19, we are notifying all student families that a student who was lab-confirmed to have COVID-19 was present on the campus of Canadian Elementary School on Thursday, 8/27. Due to privacy requirements, we will not be releasing the name of the individual or details that may identify him or her.

All students and staff that came into close contact have been notified. Those that were in close contact will remain off campus for 14 days to ensure they do not have the virus, so that there will not be any further spread.

A letter will be sent home to all CISD parents on Monday.

Dr. Pulliam

post_text:
Wildcat Fans,
Thank you for your patience as we have worked on our plans for stadium seating and ticketing for this football season. I apologize for the length of this post; however, new rules from the State, TEA, and the UIL have changed the way we will do business this year, including how we conduct UIL athletic contests. We are restricted to 50% capacity in our stadium, so we have made a number of changes to open up seating outside of the bleachers. Because of the reduced seating capacity, we have developed a prioritized seating plan to ensure that the families of our game participants have first chance to watch their children perform. CISD apologizes for any inconvenience these changes may cause. We will do our best throughout the season to adjust and improve our system, while keeping our students, staff, and community safe. PLEASE READ the attached document for SAFETY PROTOCOLS, WILDCAT SEATING PLAN, and VARSITY FOOTBALL TICKETING PROCESS. Please share this post.

post_text:
Wildcat Fans,
We are working hard to finalize our Home Football ticketing plans and we need your help. Because of COVID requirements, we will have a reduced stadium capacity. One of the groups we want to accommodate is our senior citizens. Because we must track our ticket sales in order to comply with the capacity restrictions, we are unable to do a blanket Senior Citizen pass. We would like to offer a reduced Senior Citizen rate, but we need those community members to contact the CISD Administration at (806) 323-5393 to be added to our list. Please share this post to help us get the word out to our over 65 community members. We need this information by this Friday (8/21) to be included for the first home game next week.
GO CATS!
Dr. Pulliam

WILDCAT FANS
On Tuesday, August 25, at 7:30 we will try out our new Wildcat Stadium Seating Plan with the reduced capacity and required safety measures. CISD and the Wildcat Booster Club is hosting a combined Meet the Wildcats/Pep Rally at Wildcat Stadium. For our Meet the Wildcats this year, we will only introduce high school participants in Band, Cheerleading, Cross Country, and Football – this will minimize the size of groups and number of kids we have to manage on the field. Food will not be served at this event, but the Booster Club will have tables spread out selling their various spirit items starting at 6:20pm. We will post our Stadium Seating Guidelines later this week.

GO CATS!
Dr. Pulliam

post_text:
Thanks to everyone who attended our School Board Town Hall meeting yesterday evening, both the in-person and the virtual attendees. It was a great turnout with excellent questions and relevant concerns expressed and addressed. At registration next week, parents will be asked to choose either On-Campus Learning or At-Home Learning by completing a choice form (see images attached to this post). Please read the bulleted items on that form carefully. One item not addressed at the Town Hall is the period of time students must remain in a model before switching. Students whose parents choose On-Campus Learning may change to At-Home Learning at any time. Students whose parents choose the At-Home Learning option may change to On-Campus only at the completion of the 6-weeks grading period. Students who move to At-Home due to quarantine may return immediately following the quarantine period. The forms will be available at registration at all campuses.

Have a safe and enjoyable weekend,
Dr. Pulliam

The Canadian ISD Board of Trustees will have a special meeting next Thursday, July 30th, at 6:30 at the Canadian Elementary School cafetorium. The purpose of this special meeting is to hold a public hearing over the CISD Safe Return to School Plan. We are continuing to finalize our plan and will release it to the public on Tuesday (7/28). Our hope is that parents and community members will read over the plan and bring any questions/concerns to the special meeting, which we will conduct using a town hall format. CISD Students, Staff, and Parents,

The Texas Education Agency (TEA) released guidance this week for starting the 2020-21 school year. As of now, we are planning to start on-campus instruction on our regularly scheduled date of August 19th. There will be remote instruction options for children with compromised immune systems or parents who are simply not yet comfortable with face to face instruction. CISD will adhere to TEA guidelines and guidance from local health officials to ensure the proper safety measures are implemented. We are very excited to get back on campus with students but we will do so in a way that keeps our students, staff, and community safe. As we have learned over the past months, this situation is fluid and could change before August 19th, depending on the status of COVID-19 in our county and community. As our plan to return is finalized in the upcoming weeks, we will release the details to all stakeholders.

GO CATS!

Dr. Pulliam

#strongstart

CISD Students, Staff, and Parents,

The Texas Education Agency (TEA) released guidance this week for starting the 2020-21 school year. As of now, we are planning to start on-campus instruction on our regularly scheduled date of August 19th. There will be remote instruction options for children with compromised immune systems or parents who are simply not yet comfortable with face to face instruction. CISD will adhere to TEA guidelines and guidance from local health officials to ensure the proper safety measures are implemented. We are very excited to get back on campus with students but we will do so in a way that keeps our students, staff, and community safe. As we have learned over the past months, this situation is fluid and could change before August 19th, depending on the status of COVID-19 in our county and community. As our plan to return is finalized in the upcoming weeks, we will release the details to all stakeholders.

GO CATS!

Dr. Pulliam

Here is a free opportunity for students who are serious about UIL math and ACT math.

WHO: Anyone interested in learning more about the important patterns in math, especially anyone interested in UIL Math, Number Sense and Calculator contests.

WHAT: UIL Math Summer Institute
Boost your math skills and learn new ways to think about numbers and math. We will study the fun topics in math that have cool hidden patterns and that appear on the ACT and SAT test. The emphasis will be on topics that are common on the UIL Math, Number Sense and Calculator contests.

WHEN: Each Monday from June 15 to July 13.

WHERE: High School Room S105 (Mr. Hutsell’s room)
9:00–10:00 am for elementary
10:30–11:30 am for middle school
1:00–2:00 pm for high school

TEA COVID Summer Guidelines will be followed.
Contact Steve Hutsell for information.
Steve.hutsell@canadianisd.net

SENIOR SEND-OFF on Friday!!

CISD Staff will send off the CHS Class of 2020 in style this Friday (5/22) at 12:30 with Fire Department and Law Enforcement escort. Seniors will line up their vehicles at the stadium at 12:15. We will lead them through the normal school send-off route from Wildcat Stadium to CES, down 6th Street past BES and CMS to Main Street and then south on 2nd Street all the way to Cedar and back to the stadium. Our staff will be positioned along the route in front of our campuses. We will comply with social distancing requirements along the route. Feel free to join us in your car or by standing along the route (with social distancing). Seniors, this is an optional event. We’d love to honor you if you’d like to participate. Parents are welcome to drive their senior students.

post_text:
Parent Portal Update:
We are using letter grades during this closure period for the final grading period. Because of this, parents have a somewhat altered view when looking at student progress.

Login to Parent Portal and make sure to tap on the GRADES button to the left and then click CYCLE & SEMESTER GRADES. This is where you will be able to scroll through and check for progress in relation to your student. If you are using your phone you may want to make sure you have the screen in the most horizontal position for the best view. The view from a computer screen is the most user friendly.

If you need a Parent Portal account, you need to contact your school. You will not receive grade alerts like before during closure because we are not entering numerical grades for the final grading period during closure.

It is a good idea to periodically check the portal to support your student and their progress.

We appreciate you all. Feel free to call any school or the technology office for questions.
https://youtu.be/lV6LCOtR9yk

post_text:
Governor Abbott’s Executive Order GA-14 extends current school closure until May 4. Here in Canadian ISD, we will continue to provide remote instruction. As much as possible, we want to handle learning activities and communication through online, email, and phone. For those students who do not have access to dependable internet or cell coverage, we want to practice all precautionary measures such as social distancing, frequent hand washing, and using gloves to handle materials whenever possible. Our campuses have established guidelines for picking up materials with no, or minimal, person to person interaction. If you have any questions, please contact the campus principal.

Stay safe,

Lynn Pulliam
Superintendent

shared_text:
The Citadelle Art Foundation
March 25 at 2:11 PM ·

Get ready to brighten our sidewalks! Join our community—using proper social distancing, of course—for Chalk the Walk Canadian beginning Thursday.

A new theme will be posted here each day. We invite you to chalk the walks at businesses to show your support. You’ll find chalk buckets around town.

And, while you are playing safely at home, don’t forget to chalk your own sidewalks for bike riders and walkers.

We would encourage our community to leave out buckets of chalk for kiddos and adults to participate in our daily themes. Post, Tag and share your work with friends and businesses.

Many thanks to some fun CHS art students for leading the drawings.

Let’s show Covid-19 just how strong we are together.

post_text: Canadian ISD will begin providing Grab & Go student meals tomorrow (Monday, 3/23) from 7:30am to 11:00am. Just pull through the Canadian Elementary School bus lane and breakfast AND lunch will be delivered curbside for your CISD student(s) at the same time - you will not need to make separate trips for breakfast and lunch. Your child does not have to be with you, but we will need the student's name. If you do not have transportation to CES, please call the CES cafeteria at (806) 323-6931 ext 1283. Home delivery for those who need it will start on Tuesday. Meals will continue Monday through Friday for the duration of school closure.

post_text:
Today reinforced once again that we live in a wonderful community. At 1:00 today, the snow had not melted as much as we believed it would. We started clearing off the football field, but soon had trouble with our tractor. Three quick calls to Ken King, Joe Jarosek, and Scott Brewster and help was on the way. Thanks to Ken, Joe, and Scott as well as Bryan Stephenson, Tommy Wyatt, Shannon Cochran, Lee Rodriguez, Chris Richardson, Heath Hufstedler, and Jerry Smith for helping Matt Dillon and the CISD maintenance crew. Apologies if I left anyone off. Thank to this group, our team can play, the band can march, and the cheerleaders can cheer!

Lynn Pulliam, CISD Superintendent

post_text: Good morning, Canadian! It’s going to be a beautiful day. The roads are mostly clear with some slush in town and a few icy spots on highway 33. As you drop off kids at our campuses, please be aware of trees. They are laden with heavy wet snow and limbs could break at any time. This is especially important at the west entrance to Baker (6th & Cheyenne) at the 4-way stop. Please don’t drop off kids at that spot this morning.

Canadian ISD Board of Trustees names Dr. Lynn Pulliam as the Lone Finalist for the position of Superintendent.

Dr. Pulliam most recently served as CHS principal. He previously held positions for Amarillo ISD, including Tascosa High School principal. He was named as Region 16 Principal of the Year for 2013 and 2019. Pulliam served as Texline ISD superintendent in 2000-2001. We are excited about his leadership.

post_text:
We are excited to announce that Aaron Marks has been selected as the next head coach of the Lady Cat Basketball program. Hailing from a coaching family, Coach Marks’ resume includes a current
9-year playoff streak (including a 30-win season with Farwell in 2019) and 4-time district Coach of the Year accolades. He comes highly recommended by well-respected coaches, such as Joe Lombard (Canyon), Steve Gomez (LCU), Andy Copley, and Kevin Richardson. Some common themes that came up as we asked about Coach Marks: he is a student of the game, possesses outstanding character, and is a basketball junkie. Through the interview process, it became very clear that Coach Marks is passionate about basketball but is even more focused on coaching with integrity and building positive relationships. While we are sad to see Coach Kevin Richardson go and will forever be grateful for the legacy he created here, we are very excited for the future with Coach Marks at the helm.
text:
We are excited to announce that Aaron Marks has been selected as the next head coach of the Lady Cat Basketball program. Hailing from a coaching family, Coach Marks’ resume includes a current
9-year playoff streak (including a 30-win season with Farwell in 2019) and 4-time district Coach of the Year accolades. He comes highly recommended by well-respected coaches, such as Joe Lombard (Canyon), Steve Gomez (LCU), Andy Copley, and Kevin Richardson. Some common themes that came up as we asked about Coach Marks: he is a student of the game, possesses outstanding character, and is a basketball junkie. Through the interview process, it became very clear that Coach Marks is passionate about basketball but is even more focused on coaching with integrity and building positive relationships. While we are sad to see Coach Kevin Richardson go and will forever be grateful for the legacy he created here, we are very excited for the future with Coach Marks at the helm.

HEMPHILL COUNTY HOSPITAL added 8 new photos to the album: Stop the Bleed Class 06.10.19 — with Nathan Medina and 3 others at River Valley Pioneer Museum.

Twelve students successfully completed the first Stop the Bleed class held for the public in Canadian last Monday evening. Jacob Clifton, Hemphill County EMS, conducted the class assisted by three other EMS staff, as well as Katelyn Booze HCH Director of Nursing, and Molly Kerrigan, CISD school nurse.

American Legion Post 56 wishes to thank Elizabeth Escamilla and the River Valley Pioneer Museum staff for their help.

For more information about Stop the Bleed or to sign up for the next class (date pending), please contact John McGarr at 806.323.2567 or Katelyn Booze at 806.323.1140.
